## Wiring + Breadboard Layout (Audio Front-End)

This project needs one important thing the universe will not negotiate on:

**ESP32 ADC pins cannot read negative voltage.**  
Audio is AC (swings + and -), so we must:
1) **AC-couple** the audio,
2) **Bias** it to mid-rail (~1.65V),
3) **Limit** and **filter** so it doesn’t clip or trigger on noise.

### 1) Recommended audio input circuit (simple + robust)

**Goal:** Feed the ADC a clean CW tone centered around ~1.65V with modest amplitude.

**Parts:**
- C1: 100nF to 1µF (AC coupling)
- R1: 100k (3.3V → bias node)
- R2: 100k (bias node → GND)
- C2: 10nF to 100nF (bias node → GND, optional smoothing)
- R3: 10k (series into ADC pin, input protection + helps stability)
- (Optional but recommended) D1/D2: 1N4148 clamp diodes to 3.3V and GND (over-voltage protection)
- (Optional) RV1: 10k pot as an attenuator if your audio source is hot

**Schematic (ASCII):**

Audio In (tip) ---- C1 ----+---- R3 ----> ADC_PIN (GPIO4)
|
[Bias Node ~1.65V]
|
R1 100k to 3.3V
R2 100k to GND
|
C2 10nF to GND (optional)

(Optional clamps at ADC side)
ADC node ----|<|---- 3.3V (D1)
ADC node ----|>|---- GND (D2)


**Grounding:**
- Audio In sleeve (ground) must connect to ESP32 GND.
- Keep the audio wiring short. Hum and RF hash are very real creatures.

